Never having to visit a petrol station and during summer months the income from solar panels means I pretty much do not pay for fuel. I'm a happy electric vehicle owner and have no interest in going back __	Opinionated	Positive
"My long journeys do not take any longer. My wife and I are of an age where our range is about two hours. So mid morning for loo and a coffee,, lunch time for food and loo again, afternoon tea and loo. I average 50 mph since I do not wish to drive faster so about 100 miles per 2 hours. With three comfort breaks of at least 20 minutes when I can charge at the same time, I do not need any extra charging stops. I estimate it may take 3 minutes extra per stop to charge where in my old petrol car it would have taken 10 minutes to go to the petrol station, fill up and pay. And this used electric estate car cost a comparable price to the used value of an internal combustion engine estate car. The bonus is that this car is the nicest car I have ever driven and I will never miss driving petrol after 50 years of driving one. PS where do I contact the lizard people to get them to pay me?"	Neutral	Neutral
"As an owner for 4 electric vehicle's over 8 years.... I'd be massively inconvienced going back to an internal combustion engine vehicle and having to 'fill it'.. with a very expensive liquid. If I didn't have a home charger, I'd charge at my workplace, my parents, my sister's house.. or one of the 8 sets of rapid chargers (different vendors, between 50-400KW) that are within 10 minutes drive of my house. Two rapid charger banks in a 5 minutes drive and one walking distance. And I live 10-15 miles out from the nearest city."	Opinionated	Neutral
"I'm 5 years into owning an electric vehicle, love it. I'm interested in future battery technology advances such as CATL launching and proving sodium ion batteries. They have decent energy density, use less controversial chemicals, last a very long time and most critically they are pretty much fire safe. Oh and on an exciting note they cost a lot lot less than current batteries . Another great video, thank you"	Opinionated	Positive
"Well done for doing a cards-on-the-table assessment. I agree entirely with everything you say, is the possible exception of how much a nonEV loses range in winter. I think eevee's do lose more range and the reason is that they are much more efficient. So maybe a petrol or diesel engine is throwing away maybe 60% of the fuel energy, an electric vehicle is at least 80 maybe 90% efficient. As a result, the impact of denser air etc will be more significant for an electric vehicle"	Opinionated	Positive
"Totally refreshing to hear a good honest description of electric vehicle ownership, the amount of nay sayers I have had to explain all this to. They are not for everyone yet but they suit the majority of people."	Opinionated	Positive
"If I travelled to work every day, I would spend about a minute a week on ""fuel"" as it takes about 5 seconds to plug or unplug the car. And I have a garage, so very nice when cold and wet outside. My summer range is within 10% of the EPA rating claimed. My winter range (around 15F) is about 20% less than my summer range. A winter trip that took 12 hours in my internal combustion engine sedan takes an hour and a half longer in my electric vehicle. This includes bio breaks and meals for my wife and I. I can charge for free at work most days that I drive in. Any charging that can happen while you are doing something else that you would be doing regardless of the type of car you drive is practically free wrt time. I'm just finishing my first year with an electric vehicle (2024 Ford Mustang Mach-E Rally) and have nearly 19K miles. It is the most fun to drive of any car I have owned in the last 30 years. My wife and I still have an internal combustion engine sedan which we still own, and use for those trips where it makes sense from a time, cost, or location consideration."	Opinionated	Positive
I cannot believe you filmed this next to your heat pump. it is impossible to hear you over the roaring whirring of the inefficient heat pump. it is so noisy and your house must be freezing.	Opinionated	Negative
"Thanks for the enlightenment , I still have my own views on electric vehicle ownership but great video."	Opinionated	Positive
"I started watching you when you had your leaf to try and research if I wanted to make the change. Since then benween my wife and I we have had É a leaf, i3, Niro 1st gen, kona, ioniq 5, Zoe, mini countryman E and a model 3 SR RWD Wonderful experiences with all of them. Great to drive. The pcp payments are easily on a par with the equivalent petrol cars so no extra costs. My new Tesla tracks my charging costs. I've done 1800 miles in it and it is cost me Ł80 odd. I've never ever come close to running out of charge. I didn't get them for environmental reasons. I got them because firstly a loathe burning money (literally) on fuel. And they are great to drive. I love heavy regen. I like the responsiveness."	Opinionated	Positive
"EVM - this is one of the most important videos you've done. I'm looking to buy a Kona Premium SE but have had my mind troubled by the negative press electric vehicle's are getting, some of which I dismiss because I've owned a few. My fear is buying one that is out of warranty, worried about expensive repair bills, so would you buy an electric vehicle with no warranty, yes prices are tempting but faults will no doubt be coming. Would love you to do a video on this, I cannot be alone. Thanks."	Opinionated	Neutral
"2:58 While I hope this study is correct I really doubt that it is. In my area there are lots of homes that do not have a front garden big enough to fit a car in and thus will never be suitable for charging. Equally the vast majority of flats do not have a suitable way of charging. A lot of properties will have other reasons they cannot have off street or dedicated parking. I say all this as an electric vehicle owner that lives in a flat and uses public charging, I'm lucky enough there is a park and ride with chargers just 5 mins walk from my home"	Opinionated	Positive
"Forgive the daft question; but have you ever experimented with keeping your car connected to the household gateway and exporting the charge to monetise the electricity stored during the demand peak (say through Octopus Flux) and re-charging overnight when the unit price is much lower? If so, does this have a detrimental effect on the battery by using up the finite charge cycles of a cell?...not that I have an electric vehicle, but I am working on a justification strategy for management!! __"	Neutral	Positive
"I'd love an electric vehicle, as 90% of my journeys are relatively short range, where often the engine barely gets hot. So an electric vehicle would make a lot of sense. But being retired and on a fixed income, sadly the finances dictate I'm stuck with my 11 yr old oil burner for a while longer."	Opinionated	Neutral
Never underestimate how little thinking people want to do when purchasing things.	Opinionated	Negative
"Brand new EVs will have LFP batteries which means winter charging is the same as any other season and you'll have zero fire possibility which have already been lower than petrol fire hazard anyway. it is in the name internal combustionÉ exploding our way around emitting FAsÉ forever chemicals. That's why I switched in the first place. I'ma cancer survivor. We already have nuclear bomb testing from the 1950s and 1960s to live with. No point in adding to that health burden with PFAs as soon as we can move off petrol. Industry is trying to move off fossil fuel but for them it is not an easy solve. I started in a used Nissan Leaf, an adorable car. Ridiculously fun. I live in bumpkin rural South Carolina. And with zero stations for EVs nearby, we topped off at nearby network participators, one over at a our nextdoor petrol station, one in the public parking building, another at the new courthouse. Typically network spots have 2 or 3 bays each with two car slots with one CCS and one NACS and occasionally you'll find an old CHADMO because loads of people bought the first electric vehicle models. I'm never going back. EVs are so fun to drive. Zippy a real easy aero maintenance car. I absolutely love it."	Opinionated	Positive
"the range of an electric vehicle isnt what the manufacturer quoted ...... is the same argument or complaint, as the mpg not being what an internal combustion engine car manufacturers quote ..... people always fall for it and moan"	Neutral	Neutral
"You have succesfully transitioned to EVs but i think you are missing the point my friend the reason that people are hating on them is not because they are crap its because the government are trying to take away our choice in the real world things become accepted because they become better thanthe day to day tech they live along side, people switch this government is forcing us to change to something that as yet still has a way to go and we have niether the infastructure or the access to these vehicles due to cost or living location if we had choice then eventually progress would be made and we would happily buy them, my car is 20 years old and petrol powered , it has never broken down ever and though getting slightly shabby with age it is still a reliable and economical daily workhorse, i cannot afford an electric car nor could i home charge, and i dont believe that EVs are the answer for everyone and i dont believe they are any cleaner than petrol cars they just spread their carbon footprint out, and they are astronomicly expensive to repair"	Opinionated	Neutral
"The truth about EVs after 10 years of huge government subsidies, incentives and mandates........ 3,6% of the world's personal vehicles were BEVs and Plug-in Hybrids as of January 2025. Sorry electric vehicle Man, The honeymoon phase is over. The vast, vast majority of the world's drivers do not need or want an electric vehicle. You are not saving money or the planet by driving an electric vehicle. We all have passions and obsessions. You are allowed to be an EVangelist, however, please stop trying to convince people who have basic mathematics skills and common sense."	Opinionated	Neutral
"I would argue warranties are a kind of life expectancy .Its the time the manufacturer thinks they can get away with without it breaking down. So that would suggest that EVs will last longer. Both internal combustion engine and electric can have a terminal fail ,both loose efficiency or time . Seen internal combustion engine engines die within 4 years looking at you Ford"	Neutral	Neutral
