"I am Chinese, and I also have an electric vehicle (pure electric) car, which is a 1.7-ton SUV with a 60-kWh battery. It only takes 6.6 seconds to accelerate from 0 to 100 km/h, and I have driven 8,000 km. Charging speed: It only takes 23 minutes to charge from 20% to 80%. It only takes 55 minutes to charge from 15% to 100%. My car has a relatively backward charging technology. Now high-end batteries only take 23 minutes to charge 100 degrees. Yes, you heard it right. In fact, I used to believe in internal combustion engine cars like many Chinese (especially the old predecessors), and I didn't fall in love with electric vehicle cars until I bought an electric vehicle car. The day before yesterday was Saturday, and I took my girlfriend to the beach to camp. To be precise, who was in the car, because electric vehicle cars can keep the air conditioner on and the windows closed, so there is no need to worry about carbon monoxide poisoning. Yes, the two of us slept from 2 in the evening until 10:30 the next morning, and only consumed 4.2 kWh of electricity. It is summer now, and the temperature outside is 32_. I set the air conditioner in the car to 22_, automatic gear. The battery capacity of my electric vehicle car is only 60 kWh, which is a very low-end electric vehicle car. But it has a high-speed range of 363km and a constant speed of 120km/h. The urban range (commonly known as low speed: ˛80km/h) is 503km. Both of these ranges are with the air conditioner on: 22_, automatic gear. As I said just now, my car is a very low-end electric vehicle car, and there are many high-end electric vehicle cars in China. They have a very long high-speed range, such as BYD's Tang L, with laser radar and high-level intelligent driving system, equipped with a 100-kWh battery, a high-speed constant speed of 120km/h, and can run 580km (in the southern plains). The low-speed range can reach 750km. This is a 2.6-ton SUV, and it only takes 6.9s to accelerate from 0 to 100km/h. In China, the charging fee ranges from 0.28-1.5 yuan/kWh. China implements off-peak electricity consumption, so from 0:00 p.m. to 8:00 a.m., it only costs 0.28 yuan/kWh (0.039 U.S. dollars/kWh), and even in the afternoon, charging is only 0.84 yuan/kWh (0.117 U.S. dollars/kWh). In other words, even if calculated at 0.117 U.S. dollars/kWh, if I drive 3,000 km per month, the cost of driving this car is only: 50 U.S. dollars/month, and if I drive my gasoline car, the monthly cost is: 268.78 U.S. dollars/month, obviously electric vehicle pure electric car is more economical and affordable. Some people may ask: After driving 300,000 kilometers, your car battery is scrapped. Is it expensive to replace the battery? In fact, the price of battery packs in China is now: about 400 yuan/kWh (55.7 U.S. dollars/kWh). To be precise, this is the price of last year, and the price this year will be lower. Because my battery is lithium iron phosphate battery, which is a relatively mature technology, the production cost will only get lower and lower. Back to the point, even if I replace the entire battery, it will cost $3,342, which already includes the labor cost. But under normal circumstances, I will not replace the battery. I will scrap the car and give it to the manufacturer, and then successfully buy a new car. Because in China, electric vehicles are updated every 6-8 months. I think after a few years, I will like other electric vehicles and will not want to drive the current car anymore. Just like my other internal combustion engine cars, it is quietly parked in the garage."	Opinionated	Neutral
